To date, no drug has been scientifically proven to be effective in treating the existing Ebola infection, although an experimental vaccine appears to be able to reduce mortality from the disease.
Zmapp, a combination of antibodies, had a promising field result initially, but formal studies demonstrated that it was less beneficial than expected in preventing death.
In the PALM trial, the function of Zmapp was control, i.e., the scientists used it as a basis and compared it to the other three treatments.
USA Gymnastics supports the United States Olympic Committee's note and recognizes that it is imperative that the Olympic family foster a safe environment for all of our athletes.
We concur with the USOC's declaration that the interests of athletes, clubs and their sports can be served more appropriately if progress is made with significant changes within our organization, rather than with the withdrawal of the certifications.
USA Gymnastics supports an independent investigation that may clarify how the abuse of proportion described by survivors of Larry Nassa with such courage may have gone unnoticed for so long and accepted any necessary and appropriate change.
The goal of USA Gymnastics and USOC is the same: to make gymnastics and other sports as safe as possible for athletes to pursue their dreams in a protected, positive and empowered environment.
During the 1960s, Brzezinski worked for John F. Kennedy in an advisory capacity and, later, for the government of Lyndon B. Johnson.
He advised Carter on foreign policy in the 1976 election. Later, he worked as National Security Advisor (ASN) between 1977 and 1981, after Henry Kissinger.
As National Security Advisor, he assisted Carter in the diplomatic handling of international affairs, such as the Camp David Accords of 1978, the normalization of relations between the United States and China in the late 1970s, the 1979 Iranian Revolution, which led to a hostage crisis in Iran, and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
