In addition to confirming that at least some dinosaurs were feathered, a now generalized theory also offers specific data that fossils generally do not offer, such as their color and three-dimensional structure.
According to experts, this animal has a chestnut plumage in the upper part and a pale or carotenoid hue in the lower part.
The find also allows for a better understanding of the evolution of bird feathers.
Since the feathers of dinosaurs do not have a well-developed tail, called the rachis, but do have other features of feathers (cerdas and barbulas), researchers concluded that it is likely that the rachis was the result of a later evolutionary development of these other characteristics.
The structure of the feathers suggests that their function was not related to flight, but rather was used to regulate temperature or as an indicator of it. The researchers argue that although it is the tail of a juvenile dinosaur, the specimen analyzed exhibits features of adult feathers rather than that of a pollen.
Experts' assessments were that, even though it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the specimen illustrates the plumage of an adult more than that of a pollen.
